---
// src/components/home/ContinueReading.astro — M-UX-REVIEW T1 deliverable D3.
//
// Per the 2026-04-27 UI/UX review F3 (MED) finding: in static mode the
// home + collection-landing surfaces have nothing about the user. The
// M5 mastery-dashboard slots (`recently-read`, `due-for-review`) are
// correctly gated `data-interactive-only` per the M-UX T5 contract, so
// they're invisible on the public deploy — but the public deploy is
// the only mode most visitors see. A localStorage-backed "Continue
// reading" strip costs nothing structural and replaces the empty
// space until M5 lights up the SQLite-backed surface.
//
// Contract:
//   - SSR renders an empty `<aside data-slot="continue-reading">` so
//     the slot exists in the document immediately + reflows are
//     bounded when the JS island populates it.
//   - A small inline `<script>` reads `localStorage["cs300:last-visit"]`
//     on DOMContentLoaded. If the key is present and parses, populates
//     the slot with a resume card linking back to the recorded path.
//   - If the key is absent, the script makes no DOM mutation; the
//     `<aside>` stays empty + CSS `:empty { display: none }` collapses
//     it so it occupies zero visual space (AC6).
//   - One DOM mutation per page-load. No polling, no framework, no
//     state-service round-trip.
//
// Companion files:
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_review/tasks/T1_home_surface.md (D3)
//   - src/layouts/Base.astro (the writer side — records the entry on
//     every chapter route)
//   - src/pages/index.astro (consumer)
//   - src/pages/{lectures,notes,practice}/index.astro (consumers)
//   - design_docs/architecture.md §1 (the page-chrome subsection
//     documents this client-side primitive)
//
// localStorage key: `cs300:last-visit`. Schema:
//   { path: string, title: string, scrollY: number, ts: number }
// `path` is the chapter route (e.g. `/DSA/lectures/ch_4/`).
// `title` is `document.title` at write-time.
// `scrollY` is the most-recent debounced scroll position.
// `ts` is `Date.now()` at write-time.
//
// M5 supersedes: when M5 lights up the SQLite-backed `recently-read`
// dashboard slot, this localStorage primitive becomes redundant +
// gets removed in M5's task. Until then the page actually knows you.
---

<aside data-slot="continue-reading" aria-label="Continue reading"></aside>

<style is:global>
  /* `is:global` is necessary because the inner `<span class="resume-eyebrow">`
     + `<a class="resume-link">` elements are appended dynamically by
     the inline `<script>` below — they have no Astro scoping
     attribute. Astro's default scoped-style selectors would not
     match them. The selectors are still well-namespaced (every rule
     is scoped to `aside[data-slot="continue-reading"] …`) so global
     leakage is bounded to the resume strip itself.

     `:empty` collapses the slot to zero space when the localStorage
     key is absent. The script below appends `<span>` + `<a>` when
     the key is present; the `:empty` selector then no longer
     matches and the slot renders. */
  aside[data-slot="continue-reading"]:empty {
    display: none;
  }

  aside[data-slot="continue-reading"] {
    margin: 0 0 var(--mux-space-6) 0;
    padding: var(--mux-space-3) var(--mux-space-4);
    border: 1px solid var(--mux-border-subtle);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--mux-accent);
    border-radius: 6px;
    background: var(--mux-surface-alt);
  }

  aside[data-slot="continue-reading"] .resume-eyebrow {
    /* `display: block` puts the eyebrow on its own line above the
       resume link so the inline whitespace between the appended
       elements doesn't matter. */
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--mux-fg-subtle);
    margin: 0 0 var(--mux-space-1) 0;
  }

  aside[data-slot="continue-reading"] a.resume-link {
    color: var(--mux-fg);
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: none;
    border-bottom: 1px solid transparent;
    transition: border-color 120ms ease, color 120ms ease;
  }

  aside[data-slot="continue-reading"] a.resume-link:hover {
    color: var(--mux-accent-strong);
    border-bottom-color: var(--mux-accent);
  }
</style>

<script is:inline>
  // Read the localStorage entry the writer in `Base.astro` records on
  // every chapter visit. Inline so the strip can paint without waiting
  // for a module bundle (the entire body is <30 lines).
  (function () {
    var slot = document.querySelector('aside[data-slot="continue-reading"]');
    if (!slot) return;
    var raw;
    try {
      raw = window.localStorage.getItem('cs300:last-visit');
    } catch (_err) {
      // Safari private mode + restrictive cookie configs throw on
      // localStorage access. Treat as no-entry; the empty slot stays
      // collapsed via the `:empty` rule.
      return;
    }
    if (!raw) return;
    var entry;
    try {
      entry = JSON.parse(raw);
    } catch (_err) {
      // Corrupt entry — clear it so the next visit can write a clean one.
      try { window.localStorage.removeItem('cs300:last-visit'); } catch (_e) {}
      return;
    }
    if (!entry || typeof entry.path !== 'string' || typeof entry.title !== 'string') return;
    // Origin-check the persisted path before we trust it as an href.
    // localStorage is user-writable from any tab on the same origin,
    // so the writer-side regex guard at Base.astro:473 is NOT a
    // security boundary for the reader. A malicious or self-authored
    // entry like `{"path":"javascript:alert(1)"}` would otherwise
    // produce a stored-DOM-injection on click. We require the
    // resolved URL to be same-origin; anything that resolves to a
    // different origin (or fails to parse — e.g. `entry.path = "::::"`)
    // bails out of rendering, leaving the slot `:empty` so the CSS
    // `:empty { display: none }` rule collapses it.
    // Closes M-UX-REVIEW-T1 cycle-2 security advisory.
    try {
      if (new URL(entry.path, location.origin).origin !== location.origin) return;
    } catch (_err) {
      return;
    }
    // Build a single anchor element via DOM API (avoids innerHTML so
    // the title text is escape-safe even though it comes from
    // `document.title`).
    var eyebrow = document.createElement('span');
    eyebrow.className = 'resume-eyebrow';
    eyebrow.textContent = 'Resume from where you left off';
    var link = document.createElement('a');
    link.className = 'resume-link';
    link.href = entry.path;
    link.textContent = entry.title;
    slot.appendChild(eyebrow);
    slot.appendChild(link);
  })();
</script>
